    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_648536232" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/648536232" />
    <a title="Michael Miller" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8598886-michael-miller"><img alt="Michael Miller" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1547050220p2/8598886.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/648536232?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Miller" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Miller" href="/user/show/8598886-michael-miller">Michael Miller</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8598886-michael-miller?shelf=radical-christianity">radical-christianity</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer648536232" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15405638262770672244">Radical. Well, almost. <br/> David Platt’s thesis isn’t really radical at all, though it may appear so to some. It’s just the gospel of Christ. Unfortunately, over the centuries Christians have so assimilated the gospel to their host culture and so encrusted it with traditions, that in its purer form it seems radical. The problem is not that Christians aren’t familiar with the gospel that Platt presents, the problem is, as Nietzsche said, “Even the most courageous among us only rarely has the courage</span>
  <span id="freeText15405638262770672244" style="display:none">Radical. Well, almost. <br /> David Platt’s thesis isn’t really radical at all, though it may appear so to some. It’s just the gospel of Christ. Unfortunately, over the centuries Christians have so assimilated the gospel to their host culture and so encrusted it with traditions, that in its purer form it seems radical. The problem is not that Christians aren’t familiar with the gospel that Platt presents, the problem is, as Nietzsche said, “Even the most courageous among us only rarely has the courage to face what he already knows.” We all need the courage (perhaps faith is a better word) to be as radical as Jesus demands.<br /><br /> There is so much truth in this book that is so well presented that I highly recommend it. Platt’s thesis is simply that “Christ followers in American churches have embraced values and ideas that are not only unbiblical but that actually contradict the gospel.” American evangelicalism has become a curious amalgam of biblical Christianity, jingoistic patriotism, and bourgeois capitalism. We are comfortable with a nice, middle-class, American Jesus who wishes for us to be safe and to prosper (and I would add, to have a good time). Platt believes we have blindly and unknowingly embraced these values that contradict the gospel. In this I fear he gives too great a benefit of the doubt; we see and know, but fear and doubt. <br /><br /> Even Platt, while determining to believe Jesus and obey what he says, lacks the courage at times. He decries what the American church has become: a grand building where professionals perform for the passive masses – the church of the spectacle. He (rightly) extols the fact that Jesus spent three years with twelve guys, choosing to focus on a small group. Yet while admitting he preaches in a giant building, he pleads ignorance or impotence to “reverse the trend,” and moves on. Frankly, it seems like if he obeyed Jesus on this one, he’d be out of a job – as would the hundreds of thousands of other professional ministers who need large congregations to (comfortably) support them. He is also vague on what the church’s purpose is. The only concrete action he describes is evangelism – making more disciples. As a “multiplying community,” we make more disciples, whose job it is to make more disciples. Is that all? While describing in vague terms the church as “community” where unbelievers can see the life of Christ in action, he never concretely describes what “living in community” and Christ-like actions look like.<br /><br /> Chapter 6 is a gem. It gives him pause, as it should all of us, that Christians of the past could be, not just tolerant of, but devoted to a system as evil as chattel slavery and be so certain that they were right and God was obviously on their side. His fear, and mine, is that in 150 years Christians will look back on us and find it unfathomable that we would not only tolerate, but positively embrace and extol an economic system that glorifies greed, where laying up treasure on earth is a Christian duty, where covetousness is a sacrament, and where evangelical divestment is a gospel teaching devoutly to be ignored. One of my favorite quotes from the book is in this section when he says that there will never come a day when God will say to him, “I wish you would have kept more for yourself.” He is also right on the money when he says that the real problem is that we simply don’t believe Christ enough to simply obey him on this. <br /><br /> On the question of possessions, even Platt struggles. He argues that when Jesus told the rich man to sell all and give to the poor, he was only speaking to that particular rich man in his particular circumstances and, thus, the command to him can’t be universalized. This ignores the question of why the gospel writers would include a story whose lesson is so thoroughly particularized. It also ignores the fact that Jesus himself universalizes the lesson when he says that it takes a miracle of God to convert any rich man. Finally Platt himself punches a gaping hole in his own argument when he quotes Jesus words, “Any of you who does not give up everything he has cannot be my disciple.” <br /><br /> Platt concludes with a one year plan to “a life turned upside down.” While all five of his recommendations are worthy, one wonders how he came upon these five and no others. What makes these five the most important? Other than numbers three and four, they are not particularly radical, even if they are often overlooked (praying, reading the Word, evangelizing). Number three (sacrificial giving – and he means until it really hurts) and number four (spending time in another context) are more radical. If you think giving isn't all that radical, read his recommendations first. It’s the “time in another context” that struck me. I agree with him in one sense, we do need to spend time out of our comfortable world and see others in their context, and we need to deliver the gospel to them there. But throughout the book, one of the things that struck me as so odd was that in recounting so many of his personal stories, he seems to have traveled the entire world. He encourages others to do the same. While I agree there are benefits, this seems to be an enormous expenditure of resources that could be used for those closer to home. We have all seen “mission trips” that end up being sightseeing vacations paid for with donations from well-meaning church members.<br /><br /> Overall, I found that book to be a valuable reminder of what we already know about Jesus and his gospel. I pray for the courage to be as radical as I know he demands that I be.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15405638262770672244" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

