  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_238815021" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/238815021" />
    <a title="Philip" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5010967-philip"><img alt="Philip" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1299353975p2/5010967.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/238815021?book_show_action=true">Nov 22, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Philip" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Philip" href="/user/show/5010967-philip">Philip</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer238815021" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3246070892051106319">Platt’s bestselling work documents what should be clear to most, but somehow is missed by the breadth of evangelicals – the Gospel costs something. Pastor Platt reminds the reader that the call for discipleship is a call for Christians to abandon their desires, wealth, and aspirations at the foot of the cross. The work militates against the cheap grace of the modern era that expects much of Jesus but anticipates giving little in return. Time and again, the writer brings to the readers’ minds sto</span>
  <span id="freeText3246070892051106319" style="display:none">Platt’s bestselling work documents what should be clear to most, but somehow is missed by the breadth of evangelicals – the Gospel costs something. Pastor Platt reminds the reader that the call for discipleship is a call for Christians to abandon their desires, wealth, and aspirations at the foot of the cross. The work militates against the cheap grace of the modern era that expects much of Jesus but anticipates giving little in return. Time and again, the writer brings to the readers’ minds stories of imprisoned and persecuted believers around the world who know what discipleship really means. For any believer who struggles with commitment to Christ (time to be honest), this book is a Godsend. This fascinating little work sends a powerful message to a church which has settled for lethargy. May this generation turn from the false idols of the American Dream and make a difference in the world! <br /><br />Those who criticize the supposed lack of doctrinal content or immaturity of the work need remind themselves of the issue at stake. Platt is not minimizing the Gospel, he is calling the Church to live the Gospel in all of its breadth. The writer is taking Jesus seriously when He said to “take up your cross and follow me.” With such an emphasis on tearing down the idols that keep modern Christians from following this command, it is no wonder that Platt is being accused of moralizing or socializing the Gospel. The reality is that the Church has become uncomfortable with Bonhoeffer discipleship and reacts against calls to supposed extreme discipleship.<br /><br />As a reviewer I do have a couple bones to pick with the work. Platt seems to give the reader the impression that our big churches with expensive programs and millions of dollars of wasted money would be better invested in outreach around the world. This is all well and good, but the writer seems to justify the multi-million dollar sanctuary that he preaches in every Sunday. It seems that a better explanation here would be insightful for the reader. Why not set the example by selling the facilities, meeting in houses, and giving the money to a cause in Africa or Asia? Secondly, Platt does not spend enough time clarifying how one should give to the poor. It would have been helpful for him to recommend some options or to spell out how to go about the process.<br /><br />All in all, this book is greatly needed in the shallow modern American church. Platt sounds the alarm that the danger in the blindspot is looming dangerously close and that, unless something radical is done, the Church stands to do great harm to itself. There are times when this thought shakes this reviewer to the core (pardon the personal aside here). Is it possible that my children will look at me and shake their heads at what little impact I made in the world with such a great financial opportunity just as I shake my head at the generations before me that did so little to solve the racial problems of America? Maybe its time for modern American Christianity to put down the American Dream and take up a cross and follow Christ.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3246070892051106319" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


